The kindergarten is also part of offices including architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint de Brno is the new seat of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - walls of colors, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural project society Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini-school nursery enterprise since the first drafts of the building Avriopoint.
It employs about 90 people, especially from the age of children, and it was important for women architects and project leaders to return to work quickly.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, the kindergarten school is a bonus offered to its employees by Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a work taken with care for children.
These are the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten school and with the support of management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the operational programme for human resources and the Czech Republic's State budget.
Thanks to funding (at 2.8 thousand Czech crowns) they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and after two years to provide qualified personnel as well as start-up.
After the use of the two-year funding allocation, Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and it was the Economy rating that helped to make the staffing request.
Child care is provided by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of children throughout the day.Children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they have more than three years for the most part.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can be only 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there is more to replace.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without looking at the hierarchical position.
Although it is individual care and education, the mini-school programme is comparable to that for pre-school education.
The children do not only play but also a quality education is assured - from the beginning to the preparation of the school benches they teach English.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their children and do not have the stress of a delay to go to a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus registered among companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and who are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname Maison en os.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facade recalling scales and everywhere present in the curves, here is everything that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house runs its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation one sees geometry, rhythm and order thought precisely.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit so that the impression of brightness of the colors is strengthened.
The winding and torsion of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in wave the window frames, the railings, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyelets and the blades.
The Battlo house, which stands in the Eixample district on the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy contractor, first insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepts Gaudi's idea of an unusual reconstruction and a better market.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade have also worked with other artists and creators.
The joint work for Casa Battlo's plans began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises named the house hot just after its finish because of its organic forms "the House in Bones".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening windows, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other elements of construction sculpture contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its time of central heating, with air vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi did not comply with the construction directives at that time and did not allow it to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and demanded changes.
For example, he did not like the members of the municipal council that the building pillars impede on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo demanded (and got satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third there was a private room and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which you access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by basic elements of reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also works on the modern concept of space binding.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and the high company can communicate comfortably or either limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has also received new facades a non-traditional toîture and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the interior courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-coloured game gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark which, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued to visit because they found that it was a lucrative enterprise and expanded the scope of the visits to common areas and the attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is not really expensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have 20 percent discount.
The sum is however above the price of entry into the other constructions of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
