Devices to follow people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child brings more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, originally set up to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as exemplifies that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of the little Anicka has stirred up a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that this is not a spy but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracers in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear something of this kind, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control.'
"Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything so that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," the psychologist says.
She confesses, however, that such devices can help in an assault not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and individuals, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains nevertheless."
'Cheapest devices also have an inclinometer that immediately indicates the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in an elongated position without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, the so-called intelligent mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special prologiciel.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to those used in the pendant of the size of a box of matches or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used as an autonavigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
