Men who have longer index than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer magazine.
This may depend on the level of the hormone male testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should undergo prostate cancer testing, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain over 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time close to three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right-hand index shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those with longer indexes than the annular, however, the risk decreased to 33 per cent, for men over 60 years, the risk decreased to 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, inter alia, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone matches a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Pprofessor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
