The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People must go to the Visa Requester Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the procedure for processing visas to the Embassy and consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to apply to the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC, according to their English acronyms) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will present certain advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer necessary to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another payment for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a unique payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only come to the nearest CSA where the documents will be presented and their fingerprints will be taken.
Because biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants for the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
