The CCNR considers that Mr.Dupont and his team at CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinions, but that some statements contained "the inaccurate information on social assistance, the unduly negative representations of Haitians and the coarse language that does not fit the broadcasts broadcast during the day".
The Commission also concluded that a discussion on suicide, including the dissemination of the name of two persons who had committed suicide, did not violate the broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints about comments made during broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint by the Quebec Joint Front of Social Assistance Persons.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the issue were inaccurate.
The facilitators must present solid information rather than misleading.
Regarding suicide, the host Stéphane Dupont had estimated suicide to be a cowardly gesture.
The majority of Committee members concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes at issue of "Dupont the noon" addressed a delicate subject in an equitable and appropriate manner."
No blame was therefore retained in his place.
