A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the United Nations proposed in Cancún a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries for greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction, which corresponds to nearly one third of the additional reduction required to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, with electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet to enlighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of global car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large emitter countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should shift global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will have to subtract from this balance sheet 5 Gt to stabilize by 2020 the rise in climate to 2 degrees centigrade in order to avoid becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like the ones launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consumes 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats as well as emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have posted reservations to fluocompact bulbs as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous wastes, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce waste electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost 2.5 billion.
