The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the 3rd quarter
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ITB) remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolis (9.7% counting the overseas departments), showing the corrected data of the seasonal variations (CVS) published on Thursday by Insee.
The number of unemployed is 2.631 million in metropolis.
Data from the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the working population in the metropolis and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over a year, the unemployment rate is rising by 0.1 points.
More generally, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they are available within two weeks to work and whether they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has further deteriorated, with a further rise in the unemployment rate, to 24.2% in metropolis (+ 0.9 point over three months, +0.5 point over one year) and 25% by including DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637,000 15-24 year olds were unemployed within the meaning of ILO.
The seniors, for their part, experienced a slight increase in unemployment, at 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 point over three months and over one year), i.e. 482,000 people aged 50 years or over, and 6.6% in the case of the DOMs.
Only 25-49 years of age benefited from unemployment stability in the third quarter, 8.3% in metropolis (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
Insee has no longer published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, following a controversy over its calculation method.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistical agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a 9.8% rate for France (including DOM) in October after 9.9% in September.
