Avenging hackers and diligent spies
WikiLeaks has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears only as a scandal in the face of hypocrisy which governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future dominated by regression.
But let's do it in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reported what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi is the owner), and Khadafi's sinisterly caricature profile had long been for cabaret sketch artists.
The rule that secret records should be composed only of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every repeated book (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the earlier books.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (he does not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who are dedicated to occultism believe only to what they already know, and who confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for classified files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of a limited mind) the head of secret services (unless he could be, as I know, editor in Libération), who do not hold as true as what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of states can telephone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some small performance exercises, have become spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place US diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can grasp the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims as much as the "torreals" in crisis.
But let us come to the deep nature of what has happened.
In Orwell's time, all power could be conceived like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely revealed since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the power eye.
But when one demonstrates, as it happens now, that even the cracks of power secrets cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be unveiled); it is also true that everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to remove all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put in place any reserved information - it would result in it being published on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it's just as obvious that with the current technologies, it's hopeless to be able to maintain confidential reports by phone.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the time being, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, bearing only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in single copy in closed key drawers: in the background, the Watergate spying attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving in crabs, that is, behind bars.
A century after the wireless telegrapher revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired (telephone) telegraph.
The videocassettes (analogues) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the (numerical) CDs only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With the high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communications policy and technology should return to horse-cars.
One last comment.
Once, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
It is now the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France screws up its promises of financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly released financing (such fast-start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French dolls are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU has come out of the great game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is significant and valued at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010 the EU announced €2.2 billion, making it the right way to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that the funding for "all new projects" for 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or at the overall level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there are no rules and each chooses its calculation mode.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ lent is equal to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to mitigation of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the most, it should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France only makes 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass tour!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand, the evolution of action over time and on the other, the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she believes that she spends €420 million "new and additional" in consistency with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that Bercy has achieved arbitration) could have a negative double impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely expensive...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the huge UNFCCC machine.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, lessons from this first year of early funding are essential.
First, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
